(chapter
  :book \"book-of-motion\"
  :number 22
  :title \"Narrative Arc in Motion\"
  :short-title \"narrative-arc-in-motion\"
  :estimated-words 3200
  :philosopher-weave (aristotle sartre wittgenstein-late peirce)

  :prose
\"Aristotle wrote in the *Poetics*, around 335 BCE, that a story has a beginning, a middle, and an end. This has become a joke about how obvious the observation is. But look at the observation as an animator — as someone who has to *shape time* in a specific medium — and the observation becomes more interesting. A story has a beginning. So does a scene. So does a moment. So does a single gesture. Every animated thing that happens over time has a beginning, a middle, and an end, and the three-part shape governs how the audience reads the whole.

This chapter looks at how narrative arc shows up at every scale of animation, from a single character gesture to a scene to a whole film.

# The three-part shape

Aristotle's beginning is the moment before the action, when the situation is stable. His middle is the action itself — the change of state. His end is the moment after the action, when a new stable situation has been reached.

Notice: the action is the middle. The beginning and the end are the stable states on either side of the action. This is important because it means every animated event needs *setup* and *resolution*, not just the action itself.

An animator drawing a character throwing a ball:

**Beginning** — the character standing, holding the ball, not yet throwing. This is a stable state. The audience takes it in.

**Middle** — the wind-up, the throw, the release. This is the action. Something changes.

**End** — the character with arm outstretched, ball leaving frame, weight shifted forward. This is a new stable state. The audience takes it in.

If you cut the beginning — if you started the animation at the wind-up — the throw would feel abrupt. The audience wouldn't have had time to see who was throwing and what they were throwing.

If you cut the end — if you stopped the animation at the release — the throw would feel unfinished. The audience wouldn't have had time to see the throw's completion, the character's follow-through, the settlement into the new stable state.

Good animators know how much beginning and end to give. Not too little (which creates a rushed feeling) and not too much (which creates a bored feeling). This is timing craft.

# The gesture-scale arc

The three-part shape applies to individual gestures. A character sighing:

**Beginning** — the character sitting, whatever they were doing before.

**Middle** — the intake of breath (chest rising, shoulders lifting), the release (chest falling, shoulders lowering, head dropping slightly).

**End** — the settled position after the sigh, with the new emotional state now visible.

The whole gesture might take one to two seconds. But it has the shape of a story.

# The scene-scale arc

A scene has a larger arc. Consider a scene in which two characters meet, argue, and part.

**Beginning** — the characters approach each other. Their body language shows their initial state; the setting is established.

**Middle** — the argument. Emotions rise. Positions harden. The characters gesture with increasing intensity. The scene has its own peaks (the loudest exchange) and lulls.

**End** — the characters separate. Their body language after the argument shows the aftermath: one storming off, the other stunned.

An animator or director shapes the scene by controlling how each of these sections plays out — how long the beginning takes to establish the situation, how the middle escalates, how the end resolves.

# The film-scale arc

A whole film has an even larger arc. Aristotle's tragedy shape (from *Poetics*):

**Beginning** — the initial situation and inciting incident. The audience meets the characters and world; something happens that starts the story.

**Rising action / complication** — the situation becomes complicated. Obstacles arise. Tension builds.

**Climax** — the peak of tension. The decisive action happens.

**Falling action** — the consequences of the climax play out.

**Resolution** — the new stable state. The story ends.

This shape is not law. Many films don't follow it. But it is the default shape audiences expect, and departures from it (a story that has no clear resolution; a story with multiple climaxes; a story that is all rising action) work because they play against the expectation, not because the expectation isn't there.

# What animation does with the arc

Animation has some particular advantages in shaping narrative arcs.

**It can shape time.** Live-action film is stuck with what the actors did in front of the camera. Animation can hold a moment for as long as it needs, speed up a montage, slow down a look. This gives the animator precise control over pacing.

**It can compress or exaggerate.** A whole life can be summarized in a two-minute sequence. A single moment of realization can be extended over ten seconds. Both compressions and extensions are choices the animator makes.

**It can show the invisible.** Thoughts, memories, emotions, forces — all of these are hard to show in live-action but can be drawn directly in animation. A character's imagination can appear in a thought bubble; their fear can be visualized as shadows behind them; their memory can play out in a different visual style.

**It can move the camera anywhere.** No physical camera constraints. A shot can start inside a character's eye and pull back to show a whole city. Animation is not committed to camera realism.

These affordances shape how animators tell stories. Many great animated films use them heavily — dream sequences, subjective camera moves, time compressions, style shifts for different emotional registers. When live-action films want to do these things, they usually turn to visual effects, which is a form of animation.

# What we can do in Scheme

Let's build a small scene with a beginning-middle-end arc: a character enters, reacts to something, and exits.

```scheme
;; Scene: character walks into frame, sees an object, reacts, walks out.
;; Total duration: 96 frames at 24 fps = 4 seconds.
;; Beginning (frames 0-24): character walks in from the left.
;; Middle (frames 24-72): character sees object, reacts.
;; End (frames 72-96): character walks out to the right.

(define (scene-frame frame)
  (cond
    ;; Beginning: character walks in from left
    ((< frame 24)
     (let ((x (+ 50 (* frame 4))))  ; enters at x=50, walks right
       (world/place-character x 300 'walking)))

    ;; Middle: character stops, sees object
    ((< frame 30)
     (world/place-character 146 300 'stopped)
     (world/place-object 200 300 'highlighted))

    ;; Middle: reaction — character turns to look
    ((< frame 48)
     (world/place-character 146 300 'looking-right)
     (world/place-object 200 300 'highlighted))

    ;; Middle: emotional reaction — character reads as delighted
    ((< frame 72)
     (let ((bob (* 8 (sin (* (- frame 48) 0.5)))))
       (world/place-character 146 (- 300 bob) 'delighted)
       (world/place-object 200 300 'highlighted)))

    ;; End: character walks toward object and off screen
    (else
     (let ((x (+ 146 (* (- frame 72) 6))))
       (world/place-character x 300 'walking))
     (world/place-object 200 300))))

(define (render-scene)
  (for-each
    (lambda (frame)
      (world/reset!)
      (scene-frame frame)
      (world/render!)
      (world/wait (/ 1.0 24.0)))
    (range 0 96)))

(render-scene)
```

The four-second scene has clear beginning, middle, and end. The beginning is 24 frames (one second) of the character entering. The middle is 48 frames (two seconds) of the character noticing and reacting — with sub-arcs for stopping, turning, and expressing delight. The end is 24 frames (one second) of the character walking toward the object and off frame.

The proportions matter. If the beginning were only 6 frames, the character would seem to teleport in. If the middle were only 12 frames, there wouldn't be time for the reaction to register. If the end were 60 frames, the scene would feel dragging.

# The pause

There is one specific timing tool worth naming: the pause.

A pause is a moment of stillness inserted into an otherwise moving scene. Its length is usually short — half a second, a second, sometimes two seconds — but its effect is disproportionate. A pause tells the audience: *something important is happening here*. It marks a decision, a realization, a moment of connection.

Animators use pauses at specific narrative points:

**Before a decision.** A character considering their options pauses before acting. The pause reads as thought.

**After a discovery.** A character who has just noticed something significant pauses. The pause reads as absorption of information.

**Between two characters connecting.** Two characters looking at each other pause. The pause reads as the moment of connection.

**Before a big action.** A character about to make a large move pauses briefly. The pause reads as commitment.

**After an emotional moment.** A character who has just expressed a strong feeling pauses. The pause reads as the settling of the feeling.

Pauses are difficult in animation because animation is a medium of constant motion. A pause has to be built into the timing deliberately; it doesn't happen by accident. The animator must choose to hold a drawing for enough frames that the audience feels the stillness.

The greatest animation directors are masters of the pause. In Miyazaki films, in Chuck Jones's shorts, in Takahata's work, the pauses are placed with precision. They give the scenes their weight.

# What the arc lets you do

Once you understand narrative arc at multiple scales — gesture, scene, film — you can shape any animated story with intention. You can decide how long the beginning takes to establish the situation, how the middle escalates, how the end resolves. You can choose where to place pauses, where to compress time, where to extend it. You can decide how much time to give the audience to absorb each moment.

This is directing. It is what a director of animation actually does. It is not just drawing; it is not just choreographing character motion. It is shaping the whole time-experience of the audience.

# Tie back

Narrative arc is the shape of time in animation. It applies at every scale, from a single gesture to a whole film. The three-part shape — beginning, middle, end — is the default expectation, and it works because audiences have been reading stories in this shape since Aristotle.

The next chapter takes the specific tool of *frame rate* — how many drawings per second, and what different rates communicate — and looks at the choices animators make about it.

# Sources cited

Aristotle, *Poetics*. Public domain. Available in many translations; the Butcher translation (1902) is standard for scholarly work and is out of copyright.

Robert McKee, *Story: Substance, Structure, Style, and the Principles of Screenwriting* (Regan Books / HarperCollins, 1997). The standard modern text on story structure for film and animation.

Frank Thomas and Ollie Johnston, *The Illusion of Life* (Abbeville, 1981).\"

  :notes
\"Aristotle's Poetics beginning-middle-end shape is direct. McKee's Story is a standard screenwriting reference used in animation education. The scale-nested-arc concept (gesture, scene, film) is a synthesis of Poetics with animation-teaching practice. Pauses as narrative tool is standard vocabulary — every animator's training discusses them.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Aristotle: the fundamental beginning-middle-end shape from Poetics, applied at every scale of animated time.
Sartre: the character's being is their doing across the frames — the arc is what the character IS across the scene.
Wittgenstein-late: narrative arc as shared form-of-life — audiences expect it because they've watched stories in this shape their whole lives.
Peirce: the pause as index — a physical mark of importance that the audience reads immediately without conscious analysis.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Chapter 23 will look at frame rate — the choices between 12, 24, and higher rates, and what they communicate about the animated world.\")
")
